{{Fascism in Romania}}
The '''National Italo-Romanian Cultural and Economic Movement''' ({{lang-ro|Mișcarea Națională Culturală și Economică Italo-Română}}) or '''National Italo-Romanian Fascist Movement''' ({{lang|ro|Mișcarea Națională Fascistă Italo-Română}}) was a short-lived [[Fascism|Fascist]] movement active in [[Romania]] during the early 1920s.

The movement was formed in 1921 by [[Elena Bacaloglu]], a female journalist who had an [[Italy|Italian]] husband at the time, and was an acquaintance of [[Benito Mussolini]] (she had been briefly the wife of [[Ovid Densusianu]]). The group deliberately mimicked [[Italian fascism]] and stressed the close ethnic bonds between the [[Italian people|Italians]] and the [[Romanians]].<ref>RJB Bosworth, ''The Oxford Handbook of Fascism'', Oxford University Press, p. 402</ref> The group attracted only around 100 members.<ref>Kevin Passmore, ''Women, Gender and Fascism in Europe, 1919-45'', Manchester University Press, 2003, p. 77</ref> The group was based in [[Cluj]], where it was initially established.<ref>Radu Ioanid, ''The sword of the archangel: fascist ideology in Romania'', East European Monographs, 1990, p. 74</ref> It was wound up in 1923, when it merged with the [[National Romanian Fascia]] to form the [[National Fascist Movement]].<ref>[http://hist.academic.claremontmckenna.edu/jpetropoulos/ironguard/chronology.htm Chronology of Romanian Fascism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124060223/http://hist.academic.claremontmckenna.edu/jpetropoulos/ironguard/chronology.htm |date=2005-11-24 }}</ref>

